Exploratory Data Analysis on Amazon US Dataset¶

I. Executive Summary¶

For this activity, we have performed descriptive analytics on Amazon US Customer Reviews Dataset. Our team's goal is to analyze how different products gained traction through customer reviews and ratings. We chose 10 categories, namely: Grocery, Shoes, Automotive, Electronics, Watches, Pet Products, Sports, Musical Instruments, Camera and Video Games. Given those categories, we want to understand what particular product items and categories are most reviewed, and how high or low are these rated by the customers. Since this study uses data that is approximately 33GB, we sampled only 50% for our data preprocessing. Moreover, we set a fixed random state = 42 to have consistent results in our visualizations. We dropped null values and trimmed product titles to further simplify our dataset. Exploratory data analysis was conducted and we found several interesting insights:

1.) Customers generally created reviews on electronics and sports. Moreover, Panasonic ErgoFit In-Ear Earbud Headphones, the most reviewed product, has the highest percetage of 5-star ratings among all categories. We thought of this product as a versatile, personal accessory that can be used during sports or exercise activities that's why customers dig for it.

2.) Sellers under video games category must take extra action on its products, especially since 6 of its products belong to the bottom 10 (rated 1-star) in terms of product ratings.

3.) Reviews reach its peak during December and January due to long holidays. Sellers must be able to take advantage of this information by improving their product and selling more starting from September since there is an expected increase of purchasing capacity from customers during 'Ber' months. Customers, on the other hand, must take note of reviews from helpful customers (those that have highest helpful votes) and expect discounts due to product volume increase.

4.) We clearly saw the difference of star ratings between products with no vote and with helpful votes. Those with no votes are rated relatively higher than those with helpful votes already. Amazon needs to optimize its Vine Program so that it can assist the sellers on improving the quality and review ratings of their products.

II. Introduction¶

Online shopping is one of the most prominent applications of e-commerce. It provides faster and low cost transactions, convenience, and more variety of options for sellers and customers compared to brick-and-mortar stores. Amazon, the biggest online retailer in terms of revenue and market capitalization worldwide, has the challenge to keep track of the reviews to understand the behavior of both its sellers and customers.

Prior to purchasing, Amazon customers tend to carefully read into product reviews. The absence of the ability to test a product before buying it makes the customers rely on these reviews. Typically most customers ignore average rating since they are more interested in those reviews with extreme ratings--reviews with 5-star and 1-star ratings.

Amazon sellers must be able to understand customer reviews in order to have higher rankings. Their businesses are greatly affected by reviews in such a way that if their product is given a bad review, they are at a risk of gaining bad reputation and eventually lose sales.

Amazon has been receiving million of reviews from its customers since 1995, in which opinions and experiences regarding products are shared. The rich amount of data Amazon provides can be used for academic research, particularly in Natural Language Processing and Machine Learning. This dataset is provided in order to understand customer product experiences through different methods other than what are previously mentioned.

The goal of our team is to provide a general overview of Amazon product reviews. Through this study, Amazon would know what products gained traction through the number of reviews, and the best and worst reviewed products. Additionally, looking at different product categories, Amazon would know which sellers and buyers to attract based on reviews and ratings. Understanding the nature and occurence of reviews postings, Amazon can help sellers plan the improvement of their products or release of new products.

III. Data Collection and Description¶

The dataset is a collection of more than 130M customer reviews written in the Amazon.com marketplace (1995 to 2015). It is approximately 33GB in size, including associated metadata. There is a collection of reviews in multiple languages such as US, UK, Japan, France and Germany but we only covered US marketplace for this study. The dataset is separated into product categories in tab separated value (TSV) and gzip file format each. The list of URLs for all categories available can be seen in the Amazon Customer Reviews Dataset website. Each category contains the following fields:

  • marketplace - 2-letter country code which indicates where the reviews are posted, e.g. US, UK, JP, FR, DE
  • customer_id - unique customer id
  • review_id- unique review id
  • product_id-unique product id
  • product_parent- the product displayed in search results
  • product_title- name of the product
  • product_category-category to which the product belongs to (e.g. Grocery, Shoes, Automotive, Electronics, Watches, Pet Products, Sports, Musical Instruments, Camera, Video Games)
  • star_rating - product rating based on customer review
  • helpful_votes - count of votes each review received
  • total_votes-total votes the review received
  • vine- Y(yes)/N(no); Y if the customer participates in the Vine program, N otherwise
  • verified_purchase- Y(yes)/N(no); Y if the customer who posted the review actually bought the product, N otherwise
  • review_headline- summary of the review
  • review_body- actual feedback of the customer
  • review_date - yyyy/mm/dd; the date the review is posted

The dataset for this study comes from categories chosen by our team, namely: Grocery, Shoes, Automotive, Electronics, Watches, Pet Products, Sports, Musical Instruments, Camera and Video Games.

IV. Methodology¶

Since our team works with big data of Amazon, we did parallel computing using Dask dataframe. We have the following considerations in our data preprocessing and exploratory analysis:

  1. Given the limited amount of RAM, we tested what would be the maximum sample size that can fit during data loading stage. Although the queries still work at 100% of the dataset, the .plot function is already returning an error. With this limitations and lessen encounters of errors, we decided to use only 50%.
  2. We set a sampling random state=42 for consistency of dataset used among visualizations.
  3. We dropped rows with missing entries.
  4. Erroneous data 1: In some instances, the review is in the product title field, we remove this by trimming the dataset with product titles no greater than 100 characters in length.
  5. For the computation of mean ratings and counts of reviews, we grouped data according to either month, year, product category and rating.

VI. Summary of Results¶

Based on visualizations created, we found the following results:

  • Customers generally created reviews on electronics and sports. Moreover, Panasonic ErgoFit In-Ear Earbud Headphones, the most reviewed product, has the highest percetage of 5-star ratings among all categories. We thought of this product as a versatile, personal accessory that can be used during sports or exercise activities that's why customers dig for it.

  • Sellers under video games category must take extra action on its products, especially since 6 of its products belong to the bottom 10 (rated 1-star) in terms of product ratings.

  • Reviews reach its peak during December and January due to long holidays. Sellers must be able to take advantage of this information by improving their product and selling more starting from September since there is an expected increase of purchasing capacity from customers during 'Ber' months. Customers, on the other hand, must take note of reviews from helpful customers(those that have highest helpful votes) and expect discounts due to product volume increase.

  • We clearly saw the difference of star ratings between products with no vote and with helpful votes. Those with no votes are rated relatively higher than those with helpful votes already. Amazon needs to optimize its Vine Program so that it can assist the sellers on improving the quality and review ratings of their products.
